{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601706/1938021801/0280.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWith Sunday Morning Edition\nTHEODORE W. NOYES. Editor\nWASHINGTON. D. C.\nFRIDAY... February 18, 1938\nThu Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMain Office: lltb St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office: 110 East 42nd St.\nChicago Office: 435 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014City and Suburban\nRegular Edltian\nEvening and Sunday Hoc per rno. or the per week\nThe Evening Star_45c oer mo. or 10c per week\nThg Sunday 4tar.. _. 6c per copy\nNight Final Edition\nNight Final and Sunday Star _70c per month\nNight Final Star 56c per month\nCollection made at the end of each month or\neach week Orders may be sent by mail or tele\nphone National 5000\nR*te by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance\nMaryland and Virginia\nDaily and Sunday-1 yr.. $10.00; 1 mo., 85o\nDaily only-1 yr., SH OO; 1 mo. 60c\nSunday only-.1 yr.. $4.00: 1 mo.. 4uc\nAll Other States and Canada\nDally and Sunday 1 yr.. $12.00; 1 mo.. $l.uo\nDaily only -1 yr.. $8.00; 1 mo.. 7 5c\nSunday only-1 yr., $5.00: 1 mo.. doc\nMember of tht Associated Press\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use for republication of all news dtspatcnes\n\u00abed>ted .0 \u2018t or not otherwise credited 111 tins\nSnper. 11d al,so locil news Published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special aispatcnes\nherein also are reserved.\nMuch Ado About Nothing.\nChairman Nichols, according to The\nStar\u2019s report, says that his subcommittee\nin charge of the pending tax bill does\nnot propose to allow the Commissioners\nto fix the tax rate on real estate for\ntwo reasons. First, according to Mr.\nNichols, it has been history that the\nCommissioners never voluntarily raised\nthe tax rate. Second, according to Mr.\nNichols, if the Commissioners were al\nlowed to fix the rate the question of their\nauthority to do so might be contested\nin the courts.\nFor the information of Mr. Nichols\nand the subcommittee, the Commis\nsioners have raised the tax rate, since\n1924, on three separate occasions. They\nIncreased the rate from $1.20 to *1.40.\nThey increased the rate again from\n$1.40 to $1.70. They increased the rate\nagain from $1.70 to *1.80. Under the\nlaw the Commissioners are specifically\ndirected to \u201cfix annually such rate of tax\nation as will produce the money\nneeded to defray the expenses of\nthe District during the year for which\nthe rate is fixed.\u201d In other words, they\nhave very little discretion in the matter\nand can either raise the rate, when it is\nnecessary, or face the prospect of going\nto jail.\nSince Congress adopted a lump sum\nsystem of appropriation, thereby ignor\ning unrepealed substantive law, the pro\ncedure has been to leave to the Commis\nsioners the formal announcement at the\nbeginning of the new fiscal year of the\nrate on real estate necessary to produce\nthe revenue ordered spent by Congress\nduring that fiscal year. The authority of\nthe Commissioners to fix the tax rate\nhas never been questioned in the courts.\nThere is little likelihood that it would\nbe so questioned.\nIn 1933 former Representative Blan\nton endeavored to write into the Dis\ntric appropriation bill a legislative rider\nordering the Commissioners to reduce\nthe tax rate from $1.70 to *1.50. The\nlate Chairman Buchanan of the House\nAppropriations Committee joined Mr.\nBlanton in a strong plea that the rider\nbe permitted to stay in the bill on the\nground that tax relief was due the over\ntaxed owners of real estate in the Dis\ntrict of Columbia. Regardless of Mr.\nBlanton's motives, the argument he ad\nvanced was that the real estate tax was\ntoo high and should be reduced.\nThis rider was defeated and stricken\nfrom the bill on a point of order. In\nthe following year the same attempt was\nmade to fix the tax rate in the appro\npriation bill and when the point of order\nwas raised against the rider, a curious\nparliamentary tangle followed in which,\nfor a few minutes at least and as a \u201cre\ntaliation\u201d against the gentleman who\nraised the point of order, the District\nwas deprived of any payment by the\nFederal Government, although the Dis\ntrict, of course, had nothing in the world\nto do with the point of order or any\nthing else. The lump sum was restored,\nbut the rider *yas defeated.\nMr. Nichols and the members of his\nsubcommittee are seeing things under\nthe bed when they announce their fears\nthat the Commissioners would never\nraise the tax rate on real estate if that\nempty prerogative were left to them.\nWhether they wanted to do it or not,\nwhether they thought it was just or un\njust, the Commissioners would have to\nset a tax rate sufficiently high to pro\nduce the money appropriated by Con\ngress. And why this curious tax bill now\nengaging the attention of Mr. Nichols\nand his subcommittee should be clut\ntered up with a lot of meaningless rig\nmarole about the real estate tax rate,\nwhen there are really important matters\ndeserving of their consideration, passes\nall understanding.\nIn all the discussion that proceeds\nfrom Germany there is no reference to\nthe searching comment so abundantly\nsupplied by Nletsche.\nThree-Second Spending.\nIn an extraordinary display of speed\nand with a lesson in finance that would\ntend to make the economic royalists bow\ntheir heads in shame, the Senate has\nwiped off the books of the Reconstruction\nFinance Corporation what is literally a\ndeficit of $2,653,840,000.\nAt least any economic royalist would\nhave had to call it a deficit, or charge\nIt to profit and loss. But in this case,\nwhile ostensibly only a bookkeeping\ntransaction, it nevertheless becomes a\nliability with too much realism to the\nalready overburdened taxpayers of the\ncountry. The amount represented ad\nvances which the Treasury made to the\nReconstruction Finance Corporation for\nexpenditure on relief and the activities\nof various Federal agencies. While the\nGovernment's finance corporation is in\nthe dear so far as this debt is concerned,\nB.\nthe Treasury has the liability and so\nhas the taxpayer.\nThis transaction was so speedy that\nSenator Vandenberg asked if the Senate\nwas running a \u201cthree-minute laundry.\u201d\nSenator Glass arose, and got as far as\n\u201cMr. President,\u201d when he was inter\nrupted by the Vice President, who asked\nif there was objection and the Chair\nhearing none, the bill was passed. Could\nany one envision the directors of a cor\nporation, with such a problem on their\nhands, taking the case so easily? It\nwould not be that easy for them. There\nwould be investigations, bankruptcy\ncourts, referees and the like, which would\nadd months to the final settlement.\nSenator Vandenberg aptly summed up\nthe case, after the Senate recovered from\nits shock, when he said that the measure\nwas a dramatic summary that demon\nstrates the extent to which Congress has\nused the resources of the R. F. C. to\nfinance relief and subsidies and benefits,\nand frequently in situations when it did\nnot care to confess that it was making\na direct draft upon the resources of the\ntaxpayer.\nCombating Fascism.\nAldous Huxley, in developing the\ntheme of his recent book, that means\nare never justified by the ends toward\nwhich they work, because the nature\nof the latter is colored by the character\nof the former, fears for democracy be\ncause in combating Fascism it is in\nevitably led to employ methods identical\nwith those employed by Fascists.\nIn this connection Mr. Huxley referred\nspecifically to the current competitive\nincreases in armaments. But his argu\nment seems to have suffered some con\ntradiction recently in the dispatch of\nsix American Army bombers to the in\nauguration of President Ortiz in Argen\ntina. There seems to be a sphere of\npacific struggle in vvhich the democ\nracies can meet Fascism without fear\nthat they are deserting their own\nprinciples.\nThis gesture of recently restored good\nwill between one of the leading republics\nof South America and the great republic\nwhich Latin American writers have been\npleased to designate the \u201ccolossus of\nthe north\u201d has nothing of a Fascist\ncharacter in itself, although it bears\nmarked significance as a counteraction\nto the recent spectacular flight of Bruno\nMussolini and his squadron of flyers\nfrom Rome to Rio de Janeiro, which was\njust one more overture of Fascism's Duce\nto the Latin peoples of the South.\nSix weeks earlier, in apparent response\nto the practice of Hitler and Mussolini,\nPresident Roosevelt's message to Con\ngress was broadcast to the world in six\nlanguages and a systematized schedule\nof short-wave news broadcasts in various\nforeign languages by American radio\nchains was revealed. The flight further\nspotlights the unwillingness of the Amer\ncah democracy to permit its sister repub\nlics to be lured away by a philosophy\nalien to this hemisphere and inimical to\nits democratic ideals.\nThe United States is not interested in\nmarshaling the republics south of the\nRio Grande behind a warlike program\nof revision of the status quo anywhere,\nbut it is interested in repelling as com\npletely as possible the enticement of its\nneighbors into the orbit of a political\nbloc whose objective is to overturn and\nre-establish the world order in its own\ninterest. A live attention in the United\nStates to the intangibles of friendship\nand courtesy for the Southern republics\nwill go far toward defeating the sym\npathies for Fascism, which, if intensified\namong the numerous Italian and Ger\nman populations of South America,\nmight prove a stimulus to the centripetal\nforces of that political ideology.\nMr. Huxley's view appears to have\nbeen too narrow. Democracies may be\nrisking their integrity by competing with\nFascism in warlike spheres, but a pacific\nresistance against the new theories is\nthoroughly in keeping with the spirit\nof democracy.\nMark Twain wrote interestingly on\nseveral subjects but only his laughter\nwas translated. His serious thought\nwhen it touches historic narrative re\nmains, although published to the world,\nfor only a circle of close friends.\nIndiana has developed an impressive\nliterature which includes a certain\namount of politics although press clubs\ncontinue to favor thoughts as expressed\nby George Ade and James Whitcomb\nRiley.\nA1 Capone is in a rage which appar\nently leaves him indifferent as to\nwhether his last name can be expressed\nin three syllables or two.\nSilencing the Horns.\nThe District Commissioners have un\ndertaken an interesting, albeit drastic,\nexperiment in prohibiting the blowing\nof automobile horns from midnight to\n7 am.\nCertainly, the chronic nocturnal horn\ntooting pest had it coming to him. Traf\nfic Director Van Duzer and the Com\nmissioners apparently have had their\nown personal experiences with this type\nof nuisance. Few citizens have escaped\nhis ear-splitting, sleep-disturbing, nerve\njangling breaches of the public peace.\nSome persons have been disposed to\nlook with a degree of tolerance on such\noffenses, cognizant of the fact that a\nromantic swain may be signaling his\nsweetheart. The sentimentalists feel\nthat nothing should be done to inter\nfere with the orderly course of true ro\nmance. There comes a time, however,\nwhen even sentiment is likely to be\ndriven out of the window by the per\nsistent blasts of an automobile horn\nIn the street below.\nThere are other varieties of post\nmidnight horn-tooters, some of them\nseemingly beset by pure fiendishness,\nbut the racket they make sounds the\nsame to any ear. They are all to become\noffenders by a swoop of a Commissioners\u2019\npen.\nThis is as it should be, in view of\nforthright, peace-loving citizens. The\nban, however, has been made so sweep\ning that even the peace-loving citizen Is\nprohibited from sounding so much as a\nfeeble toot, once the hour of midnight\nhas struck. Only police, fire and other\nbona fide emergency vehicles are ex\nempted from the order. No exception Is\nmade for the private motorist who, sud\ndenly confronted with a pedestrian in\nthe middle of a dark street, instinc\ntively moves to sound a warning of dan\nger. This will be bewildering to the\ncareful driver who has been taught all\nthese years that it was his duty to give\na reasonable warning to unwary persons\nor animals In his pa**:.\nMr. Van Duzcr, anticipating these\nprotests, says''the privilege of tooting\nhorns at night has been abused by many\ndrivers, exhilarated by the switching off\nof crossing lights or whatnot. This has\ngiven rise to speeding and general reck\nlessness and resulting accidents. The\ntendency has been, he asserts, to depend\non the horn rather than the brakes when\nobstacles are encountered.\nUndoubtedly, the police will exercise\ndiscretion in making arrests under the\nnew order. Otherwise they may have to\nface the embarrassing task of arresting a\ncareful driver for saving some one s life\nby sounding a horn in the still of the\nnight.\nBusiness Outlook.\nUndismayed by current fears fr- the\nfuture of business, officials of the Capital\nTransit Company have decided to spend\n$1,000,000 on new equipment which will\nenable them to improve the service they\nrender the public. That decision is\nlaudable in two respects.\nIn the first place, it reflects a dis\npassionate and intelligent attitude to\nward the present and future business\nsituation. Some business men, alarmed\nby existing conditions, have been un\nwilling to make any capital improve\nments. It may be that in some lines of\nbusiness such caution is justified, but\nthere is no gainsaying the fact that de\npression is prolonged and intensified\nwhen business men as a class retire to\ntheir storm cellars and remain there\nuntil prosperity comes to them.\nIn the field of public transportation\nthere is good reason to believe that\nrevenues are governed in large meas\nure by the quality of the service offered\nthe public. Officials of the transit com\npany have shown a determination to\nrender the best possible service, expect\ning in return an increasing number of\npatrons. That this expectation is well\nfounded is indicated by the readiness\nwith which local banks subscribed to the\nmillion-dollar loan.\nThis business principle applies not only\nto street car and bus companies, but to\nvirtually, all lines of activity. Before\nbusiness men as a class resign them\nselves to a hopeless future they should\nbe sure they have made every prudent\neffort to improve whatever product they\nhave to sell. The American public has\ndemonstrated its willingness to spend\nmoney if it receives full value in return.\nThe word \"love\u201d is so freely used in\ncurrent literature that it brings readers\nback to old times when it was used with\nheavy effect in popular literature. But\nplayers still offer Julius Caesar, which\ndeals with masculine sentiment rather\nthan with amorous relations.\nShooting Stars.\nBy PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nFishing.\nEverybody's flshin', everywhere you go,\nFishin\u2019 fur a bank account or flshin\u2019\nfur a beau;\nFishin' fur a compliment that may be\nfalse or true;\nFlshin\u2019 fur position to command the pub\nlic view.\nFishin\u2019 fur a place in life to call your\nvery own.\nFishin' fur a fireside warm or flshin\u2019\nfur a throne.\nEverybody\u2019s flshin', an\u2019 you need a\nholiday\nTo do a little flshin' in the plain old\nfashioned way;\nFishin\u2019 in the big outdoors, beside the\nwhisperin' stream.\nWhere, when the fish ain\u2019t bitin\u2019, you\ncan doze an\u2019 maybe dream.\nYou sort o\u2019 want to concentrate upon\nthe simple wish\nTo do some real flshin\u2019 just fur ordi\nnary fish.\nThe Living Present.\n\u201cFuture generations may raise monu\nments for you.\u201d\n\u201cBui what I want to know,\u201d said Sena\ntor Sorghum, \u201cis whether the present\ngeneration will raise a campaign fund\nfor me.\u201d\nJud Tunkins say* fame just naturally\ncomes to some people. George Wash\nington got more credit for chopping a\ncherry 'tree than anybody else could\nget for breaking up a cord of wood.\nAn Egotistic Inquiry.\nWhy is it what I have to say\nSeems such a serious matter,\nWhile thoughts of others on display\nAppear but idle chatter?\nIdentification Demanded.\n\u201cDid you receive any valentines?\u201d\ninquired the bashful man.\n\"Only one,\u201d answered Miss Cayenne,\nlooking him straight in the eye. \u201cI\nthrew it into the waste basket. I never\npay any attention to anonymous com\nmunications.\u201d\nx\u201cI do not deny that the world is get\nting better,\u201d said Hi Ho, the sage of\nChinatown, \u201cbut as it improves, it makes\nsome of the people In it seem worse and\nworse by contrast.\u201d\nMusings of a Motor Cop.\nAs traffic rules are made anew\nTo check the whirl so dizzy,\nIf I enforce Just one or two,\nI\u2019ll keep my whole day busy.\n\u201cTrouble comes easy.\u201d said Uncle\nEben. \u201cYou has to hunt work, but it's\nalius easy to find a crap game.\u201d\nY WH\nTHE POLITICAL\nMILL\nBY G. GOULD LINCOLN.\nIf there is anything in the coalition\nidea\u2014as advanced by Senator Vanden\nberg of Michigan\u2014the Republicans and\nthe Democrats opposed to the New Deal\nmight make a beginning in Indiana.\nThere Senator Van Nuys, Democrat, who\nincensed the White House and angered\nthe Democratic organization of his State,\nby his pronounced opposition to Presi\ndent Roosevelt\u2019s court bill last year, is\nup for renomination and re-election.\nWhat\u2019s to prevent the Republicans from\ngetting back of Van Nuys\u2014giving him\nthe party indorsement or actual nomi\nnation, if it desires? Nothing, except\nthe desire of the Republicans to elect\na Senator from their own ranks and the\ndesire of the G. O. P. to stay alive.\n\nVan Nuys. realizing that Gov. Townsend\nand presumably Paul McNutt, who put\nTownsend in his present office, are Intent\nupon defeating him for renomination\nand re-election, has announced that\nhe will be a candidate with the intima\ntion he will run as an Independent Demo\ncrat if the party organization turns him\ndown. It looks like a bid for Republican\nas well as Democratic support. Unfor\ntunately, perhaps, for Van Nuys, a num\nber of Republican aspirants for the Sen\nate seat he now holds are already quietly\nin the race for the nomination. Former\nSenator James E. Watson is one and\nothers include Walter Bossert of Liberty,\nformer Republican district chairman and\nformer head of the Ku Klux Klan in the\nState, and Dick Wills of Kokomo. So\nthe coalition idea, unless these Repub\nlicans in Indiana change their present\nattitude, does not seem to be doing w'ell.\n\nRepublican leaders in Congress, out\nside of Senator Vandenberg, shake their\nheads over the coalition idea as sug\ngested by the Michigan Senator in his\nLincoln Day address. They do not be\nlieve it will work in Indiana or in New\nYork, Nebraska, Missouri, Nevada or any\nother State where anti-court Democratic\nSenators come up for re-election. In\nother words, unlike Senator Vandenberg,\nthey are unwilling to go to the length\nof foregoing the identity of the Repub\nlican party to defeat the New Dealers.\nTheir attitude is that if the G. O. P. will\njust hang on and wait, its day will come\nagain. They see plenty of trouble al\nready ahead of President Roosevelt and\nhis followers\u2014partly due to the depres\nsion and partly due to the new crop\ncontrol bill and a real division in the\nranks of labor.\nNor do these leaders take much stock\nin the railing of Gov. Aiken of Ver\nmont against the Republican leader\nship\u201d of today, of which Gov. Aiken said\nAbraham Lincoln would be ashamed if\nhe were alive. To them this is an old\nstory. They interpret the Governor's\nattack as an attack upon Herbert Hoover\nand Alf M. Landon. but they insist that\nneither of these gentlemen is leading\nthe Republican party today, and that\nGov. Aiken should understand that. The\nold guardsmen in Congress and for the\nmost part in the national committee are\n\u2018\u2018out.\u201d So they do not see why the Ver\nmont Governor should be so excited over\nthe leadership of the party toodv. Those\nRepublicans still holding elective office,\nlike Gov. Aiken himself, are the leaders\nof the party, they insist.\nA coalition of anti-New Deal Repub\nlicans and anti-New Deal Democrats\u2014\nif it means a conservative alignment\nagainst the liberal and radical elements\nin the country, these Republican leaders\ninsist, would get nowhere. They are\nconvinced\u2014just as President Roosevelt\nis convinced\u2014that the liberal and radi\ncal voters would outnumber the con\nservatives four or five to one. What the\nG. O. P. must do. they hold, is not to\nline up with the conservative Demo\ncrats, but to win to the Republican ban\nner many of the liberal and independent\nvoters. They believe this will be done\njust as soon as the people begin to get\nsick of the present administration, .\"hat,\nthey maintain, is only a matter of time.\nNothing stays the same. All comes round,\nthey maintain, to him who will but\nwait It may be so, but on the other\nhand, it may be a long and drearv wait\ning.\n\nSenator Van Nuvs\u2019 declaration that\nhe would go into the Senate race ir\nrespective of what might be the atti\ntude of the McNutt or Gov. Townsend\ncame almost on the heels of the pub\nlication of plans to give Paul V. Mc\nNutt, former Governor and at present\nUnited States High Comissioner to the\nPhilippines, a big reception in the Na\ntional Capital next week. Mr. McNutt is\nambitious. He wants to be President, and\ntherefore he is a candidate for the Dem\nocratic nomination for that office in 1940.\nHis friends have decided apparently\u2014\nand probably with his consent\u2014to rush\nhim to the fore, hoping to keep him\nthere for the next couple of years.\nThis is a dangerous proceeding. Mc\nNutt will be the target of the brickbats\nof all the other potential candidates\u2014\nwho have not yet raised their heads.\nHowever, it seems to be the plan of cam\npaign. He is to be given a reception\nhere by Senator Minton of Indiana\nwhen he comes to the Capital to report\nto President Roosevelt on the conditions\nin the Far East. This reception, accord\ning10 f,11.reP\u00b0rts' to be a huge affair,\nwith all important Democrats invited,\nand a big crowd coming here from In\ndiana for the occasion. Before McNutt\ngets to Washington he plans to stop off\nn Denver and particularly in Indianapo\nlis, where he will attend the banquet\nor the Indiana Democratic Editorial\nAssociation. Probably he will be men\ntioned there as the next Democratic\nnominee for -President\u2014and his boom\nwill have been launched, even before\nhe gets to Washington.\nA di a.\nMcNutt has been national commander\nof the American Legion. He has been\nGovernor of Indiana. He knows a good\nbit about politics. Possibly his present\ntactics are not so bad as some other\nDemocrats aopear to believe. It has\nif1} reported he will quit his present\njob in the Philippines flext Summer and\ncome back to this country. He could,\nif he wished, become a candidate for\njeneto- against Van Nuys. But there\nhas so far been no indication that he in\ntends to take such a course. He seems\nto Drefer to be. the Dower behind the\nthrone in Indiana Democratic politics.\nThe former Governor of Indiana may,\nwhile he is at the White House, under\ntake to find out for himself whether\nthe President intends to seek a third\nterm. Undoubtedly a determination on\nthe part of the President to continue in\nofflee would have the effect of taking\nMcNutt out of the race, and he would\nlook around for some other job\u2014possibly\npresident of the Indiana State Univer\nsity.\n\nLike the late Calvin Coolidge in 1928,\nPresident Roosevelt today is the dark\nhorse !n the White House. And he is\nlikely to remain so for some time, un\nless, indeed, Mr. McNutt is able to pry\nloose some information, more definite\nthan has yet been forthcoming about\nthe President\u2019s future plans. Yet there\nare many of the administration Officials\nwho frankly believe that the President\nwill not seek another term of offlee.\nA\nTHIS AND THAT I\nBY CHARLES B. TRACEWELL.\nAfter a person gets used to cats, as\npets, dogs don\u2019t seem to have much\nsense.\nWays and habits of these two tribes of\nanimals are so different that there is no\nreconciling them.\nA small black spaniel had come up on\nthe back porch to sample a deep bowl of\nsalmon put out for the outside cat.\nSuddenly a pal of his, a bird dog,\nappeared upon the scene, poking its\nspotted nose over the rim of the porch\nfloor.\nRemember, these two dogs were pals.\nThey lived together, and got along very\nnicely, as good pals should.\nBut what happened now?\nThe spaniel began to tremble violently,\nthen faced its friend, and began to growl\nand bark.\nThe entire action seemed opposed to\nsensible tactics. Cats, the observer felt\nsure, would never have acfed so.\n\nThere is, of course, a rough and ready\nway to canine actions seldom if ever\nfound among the cats.\nTheir paws are harsh and clumsy, in\ncomparison with those of a cat.\nTheir claws, too. are always out. The\ncat is able to draw' its claws in or put\nthem out at will.\nA cat's claws are not always extended\nin anger.\nTheir extension is one of the three\nstandard ways of showing feline pleasure.\nThis is commonly shown in the action\nsometimes known among their friends\nas \u201cmaking bread.\u201d\nEspecially on a soft cloth, or other\nsurface, a cat likes to stick out its claws,\nand push them into the material time\nand time again. This kneading action\nis one of the most typical cat movements.\nPurring, of course, is the best known\nof the three ways of showing pleasure.\nThe last is the yawn.\nYawning is a cat's way of showing sat\nisfaction, as well as of greeting his\nfriends.\nSpeak to a cat aslpep. and it will do\none of two things\u2014stretch its legs and\nstick out its claws, or yawn.\nThe cat's yawn is a peculiar and sig\nnificant greeting.\nThis animal has taken what, would be\nequivalent to ill breeding, among hu\nmans, and made it into a most delicate\nsign of affection.\nThe trouble with people who say cats\nhave no affection is simply that they\nhave never taker, the time to study the\nanimal, and to find out in what peculiar\nways it greets its friends.\nThe yawn, after all, need not be merely\na sign of indifference or ill breeding.\nThe smile is not so regarded, and a\nyawn is just another sort of smile, in a\nsense.\nSince there can be no human thoughts\naccompanying it, the cat's yawn can be\ntaken solely as a real greeting, a signifi\ncant way of saying. \"Hello, there, how\nare you?\u201d\n\nDogs come bounding tip to one in the\nmost boisterous way, as if aiming to\nknock one down.\nCats, never.\nA cal walks up with grace, tail held\nhigh.\n1\nPerhaps the dog\u2019s action most lacking\nin plain common sense is chasing auto\nmobiles.\nYou will never catch a cat doing that.\nBut dogs do it for sport, let us say, to put\nthe best interpretation on it.\nSomething moving along, something\nthat does not belong to one\nIt is not fair to blame the dog, but the\naction does not bespeak much brains.\nNo doubt it doesn\u2019t show much brains\non the part of dog owners, either, that\nthey permit their pets to chase machines\nof steel.\nBreaking a dog of this bad habit is\ndifficult, but it has been done. Several\ndevices to achieve the desired result have\nbeen patented, but a little time and\npatience will get the same result.\nThe dog is watched, and when it chases\nafter a car, it is recalled, a folded paper\nsmacked vigorously on the hand, which\nis held over the rear portion of the\nanimal.\nIt is not necessary to hit the dog.\nThis requires some time, however, and\ntime seems to be what most modern dog\nowners, except at shows, have little of,\neven for their pets.\n\nThe bark of the dog is what the cat\nadmirer shrinks from most of all.\nThis harsh, ugly noise is so different\nfrom the ordinary or extraordinary meow\nor yowl of the cat that it strikes the\near as a cross between a fog horn and\nan old rattletrap automobile coming\ndown the street.\nThe strident note in the dog\u2019s bark was\nput there for exactly the same purpose\nof the automobile horn, as a warning.\nThe creature, therefore, can be blamed\nfor the harsh quality of its note no more\nthan the automobile horn.\nThe cat friend, however, will find it no\nmore pleasing because it is the best the\nanimal can do.\nThe soft meow of the cat, on the other\nhand, he finds exactly right.\nEven when the creature is yowling In\nthe night, its friends find much td admire\nin its clear notes, somewhat resembling\nthose of a highlv paid coloratura soprano.\n\nCats. too. are vastly more friendly than\ndogs, and show more sense about it.\nSome dogs never learn friends from\nfoes. Fox terriers, in particular, are no\ntoriously silly in this regard.\nThey will bark at the same person dav\nafter day.\nHunting dogs show more sense. They\nmay bark the first time a stranger comes\nalong, but let him make a regular habit\nof his walk, and the dogs will shortly get\nonto the fact, and let him walk in peace.\nFox terriers never; they bark as furi\nously upon the hundredth appearance as\nupon the first. This may be proving\nthem good watchdogs, but the essence of\ngood watching is showing some sense.\nNeither dogs, cats nor humans can escape\nfrom the necessity of what has been\ncalled, for want of a better term, plain\ncommon sense.\nAs sensible creatures, cats seem to have\nthe edge on dogs. They take life as they\nfind it. and try to make the best of it.\nThey are more friendly, given half a\nchance, and are affectionate enough.\nThey do not make harsh noises just for\nthe sake of making them. They do not\ngrowl at their best friends, nor menace i\ntheir pals that come for a taste of salmon.\nWASHINGTON OBSERVATIONS I\nBY FREDERIC WILLIAM WILE.\nWhen Solicitor General-to-be Bob\nJackson told the Senate Judiciary Sub\ncommittee this week that speeches\n\u201caround here\" are rarely \u201coriginal ex\npressions.\" and that he and Secretary\nIckes both \"stole\" from the same source\nphraseology for their recent crackdowns\non big business. Jackson started some\nthing. Among the things he set in\nmotion was this observer's recollection\nabout a strange similarity between the\nperoration of President Roosevelt's fa\nmous \"Now!\" victory dinner blast of\nMarch 4, 1937, and language used by\nStuart Chase, economist, writer and\nlecturer, and one of the Boswells of the\nNew Deal, just a few days earlier. It\nis evident that whoever was then re\nsearching, ghost-writing or otherwise\nbrain-waving for F. D. R.. didn't have\nany compunction about subjecting even\nthe President of the United States to\na charge of plagiarism.\n\nMr. Chase had written a letter to the\neditor of the New York Times on Feb\nruary 15. 1937, about the Roosevelt\nSupreme Court proposal. Although the\nletter was never published, it was read\ninto the Congressional Record by Sena\ntor Bob La Follette on February 24,\nwhere, apparently, the eagle eye of the\nWhite House speech-w'ritlng aide lit upon\nit. Later. La Follette circulated a re\nprint of the letter. In a dozen striking,\nstaccato phrases. Chase pictured the\nplight of 6,000,000 farmers embittered\nby the court's A. A. A. decision; of 15.\n000.000 workers hit by the N. R. A. an\nnulment: of 500,000 coal miners and op\nerators disgruntled by the Guffey act\nruling; of 1,000.000 railway men aroused\nover the knockout of the retirement act;\nof 8,000,000 unemployed; of America's\nlandless tenantry; of child labor; of the\ndemoralized stock market; of the\nravages of flood, drought and dust\nstorms, etc., etc.\n\nGet a load of this. Mr. Chase said:\n\u201cThe Ohio River is not conversant with\nthe interstate commerce clause.\u201d At\nthe victory dinner President Roosevelt\nsaid: ''The Ohio River and the dust\nbowl are not conversant with the habits\nof the interstate commerce clause.\u201d Said\nChase: \u201cOnly vigorous action, inaugu\nrated by the Federal Government\ncan cope with this appalling situation.\u201d\nSaid Roosevelt: \u201cFloods and droughts\nand agricultural surpluses, strikes and\nindustrial confusion and disorder can\nnot be handled forever on a catch-as\ncatch-can basis.\u201d\n\nNow for the \u201cNow!\" coincidence. At\nthe close of his Times letter, Chase said:\n\u201cWhat is the President to do?\nHere are all these farmers and workers.\nNow. Here are women laboring 48 hours\na week in New Bedford mills for $5.\nNow. Here is the dust bowl beginning\nto blow again. Now. Here are millions\nof landless tenants progressively sliding\nto economic perdition. Now. if we\nreally cared about America, I think we\nshould act. Now.\u201d\n\nHere's how the President wound up\nat the victory dinner: \u201cHere is one\nthird of a nation ill-nourished, ill-clad,\nill-housed\u2014Now! Here are thousands\nupon thousands of farmers wondering\nwhether next year\u2019s prices will meet\ntheir mortgage interest\u2014Now! Here are\nthousands upon thousands of men and\nwomen laboring for long hours in fac\ntories for inadequate pay\u2014Now! Here\nare thousands upon thousands of chil\ndren, who should be at school, working\nin mines and mills\u2014Now! Here are\nstrikes more far-reaching than we have\never known, costing millions of dollars\u2014\nNow! Here are spring floods threatening\nto roll again down our river valleys\u2014\nNow I Here is the dust bowl beginning\n-1\nto blow agam\u2014Now! If we would keep\nfaith with those who had faith in us.\nif we would make democracy succeed I\nsay we must act\u2014Now!\u201d\n\nThere's a boom for former Gov O\nMax Gardner of North Carolina as czar\nof radio. The National Association of\nBroadcasters, in session at Washington\nthis week, appointed a committee of re\ngional directors who will next month\nchoose a Kenesaw M. Landis-Will H.\nHays for the wave lengths, at a salary\nreputedly in the neighborhood of $50,000.\nMr. Gardner recently renounced attrib\nuted ambitions to become the first paid\npresident of the New York Stock Ex\nchange. The fact that the one-time\nTarheel executive hails from the same\nneck of the woods as Chairman McNinch\nof the Federal Communications Com\nmission is supposedly one of Gardner s\nchief claims to eligibility for the broad\ncasting .job Since leaving office at Ra\nleigh in 1933. he has been active at\nWashington as counsel for the cotton\ntextile and rayon industries. The ex\nGovprnor rates as having an inside track\nto the White House, because he was an\noriginal Roosevelt, man in Dixie.\nDiplomacy has again raided the Wash\nington newspaper corps. Following the\nexample of Ambassador Joe Kennedy in\ntaking Harold Hinton of the New York\nTimes to London as his public relations\naide. Ambassador Joe Davies has drafted\nStanley Richardson of the Associated\nPress for similar service at Moscow.\nRichardson represented the A. P. in\nRussia before, during and after Ameri\ncan recognition of the Soviet, and knows\nthe game there thoroughly, including\nspeaking and reading fluency in the\nlanguage. He's a Virginian, a star re\nporter. and has covered the State de\npartment for the A. P. for the past\ncouple of years. Richardson will later go\nto Belgium with Ambassador Davies.\n\nBy the Society of Woman Geographers\nat Washington there's just been issued\na 27-paged brochure in remembrance\nof Harriet Chalmers Adams, its first\npresident and late wife of Dr. Frank\nlin P. Adams, former counselor of the\nPan-American Union. Mrs. Adams was\na pioneer in the field of practical geogra\nphy. From girlhood, exploring far cor\nners of the earth, in order to interpret\nthem to others, was her consummate in\nterest. On the lecture platform, because\nof her gift for dramatization, she made\nremote peoples live and breathe for her\naudiences. Through her pen and camera\nshe reached millions more in the pages\nof geographical publications. Mrs.\nAdams traveled more than 100.000. miles\nacross South America, Europe and Africa.\nThe realms of study in which she spe\ncialized were the American aborigines\nand the Spanish countries and posses\nsions. A tragic accident that befell her\nin the Balearic Islands in 1926 prevented\nthe continuation of strenuous explora\ntion. The S. W. G. has established the\nHarriet Chalmers Adams Memorial En\ndowment Fund to continue the research\nwork long conducted for the society by\nMrs. Adams out of her own time and re\nsources.\n\nAnother aboriginal New Dealer has\ncome into his reward\u2014Michael Francis\nDoyle, Philadelphia lawyer just ap\npointed by President Rosevelt to suc\nceed the late Newton D. Baker as a\nmember of the Permanent Court of Ar\nbitration at The Hague. Doyle was the\npatentee in March, 1933. of the idea of\nhaving Democratic presidential electors\nassemble at a Capital lovefeast on the\neve of F. D. R.\u2019s inauguration. He has\nlong been active in League of Nations\naffairs, for the past 15 years as chair\nman of the American Committee at\nGeneva, a self-supporting body which\nrenders valuable service to Yankee visi\nw\nANSWERSTO\nQUESTIONS\nBY FREDERIC J. HASKIN.\nA reader can get the answer to any\nquestion o) fact by writing The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J.\nHaskin, Director, Washington, D. C.\nPlease inclose stamp lor reply.\nQ. How is a race horse\u2019* aaliva tested\nfor dope?\u2014H. T. P.\nA. Samples are analyzed by thoroughly\ntested chemical procedures not radically\ndifferent from those customarily used in\ntoxicological work. By this procedure\nany one of at least 40 different drugs\nmay be detected.\nQ. What are the five largest life In\nsurance companies in the United States?\n\u2014W. H. G.\nA. They are as follows: Metropolitan.\nPrudential, New York Life, Equitable\nLife and Travelers.\nQ. What salaries do college professors\nreceive?\u2014S. L.\nA. The Office of Education saj\u2019s that\nprofessors\u2019 salaries vary from a low me\ndian of $2,606 to a high median of $4,676\nin different types of publicly controlled\ncolleges and universities and from $1,662\nto $5,733 in groups of privately controlled\ncolleges and universities.\nQ. Please give a list of aviation tro\nphies?\u2014W. H.\nA. A partial list is as follows: Cheney\nAward. Collier Trophy. Columbian Tro\nphy, Conway Trophy, Distinguished Fly\ning Cross, Greve Trophy, Daniel Gug\ngenheim Medal. Harmon Trophy, Hub\nbard Gold Medal, King's Cup, Loening\nIntercollegiate Trophy. Frank Luke, Jr.\nMemorial Trophy. Mackay Trophy, Man\nly Memorial Medal. Mitchell Trophy. Syl\nvanus Albert Reed Award, Herbert SchifT\nMemorial Trophy. Shell Trophy. Shell\nCup. Thompson Trophy, and Wright\nBrothers Medal.\nQ Is the percentage of cars in poor\ncondition large?\u2014J. W.\nA. In the Casualty and Surety Under\nwriters\u2019 inspections of 22,000,000 cars in\n42 States. 75 per cent were found to have\ndefects which increase the hazards of\ndriving.\nQ. Is Louise Fazenda, the movie act\nress, marired \u2014J. L.\nA. She is the wife of Hal Wallis, a\nstudio manager.\nQ Who wrote the poem containing\nthe line. \"How far the gulf stream of\nour youth may flow into the Arctic re\ngions cf our lives\"?\u2014W. H\nA. It is from Longfellow's \u2018\u2018Morituri\nSalutamus.\u201d\nQ. Hew much time is lost in this coun\ntry by strikes?\u2014C. F. G.\nA. The International Labor Office Year\nBook reported that in 1936 the United\nStates lost 13,901,956 days in 2,172 dis\nputes, involving 788,648 workers.\nQ. Did the people of olden times have\nany idea of the value of tobacco as a\ncrop?\u2014K. H.\nA. In 1613 Robert, Harcourt, an Eng\nlishman. wrote: This commodity (to\nbacco) will bring as great benefit and\nprofit as ever the Spaniards gained bv\nthe best and richest silver mine in all\ntheir Indies.\nQ. What is a franc-tireur?\u2014F. J.\nA. The term is French and applied to\nthe French army means a skirmishing\nor scouting sharpshooter.\nQ. When was the coal mine disaster at\nScofield. Utah?\u2014H. E.\nA. The disaster occurred on May 1.\n1900, and 200 were killed.\nQ. What is the origin of figure skat\ning in the United States?\u2014L, F. H.\nA. In 1864. Jackson Haines, a master\nof ballet and ice skating in the United\nStates, went abroad where he successful^\ncombined dancing and skating. He was\nso popular that when he died, in 1875.\nthe natives of Finland marked his grave\nwith the words. \"To the American Skat\ning King,\" After his death interest in\nthe sport lagged until about 1908, when\nIrving Brokaw of New York won an in\nternational prize at St. Moritz and\nbrought back to this country the conti\nnental style, which Haines had orig\ninated.\ni Q For whom is Tulane University in\nNew Orleans named?\u2014H. L.\nA. It is named for Paul Tulane. for\nmany years a merchant of New Orleans.\nwho gave generously for the higher edu\ncation of young people in that city.\nQ. Who is eligible for a Carnegie Hero\nFund Medal?\u2014L. B.\nV Men and women who follow peaceful\nvocations on land and sea of the United\nStates. Canada, and Newfoundland, and\nwho perform heroic acts are eligible for\nrewards of the Carnegie Hero Fund Com\nmission.\nQ. How much tea is used in the United\nStates?\u2014W. L.\nA. Last year 95.552,828 pounds of tea\nwas consumed in this country.\nQ. Please give a list of some of the\nradio programs (not orchestras! that\nhave been on the air the longest?\u2014J. W.\nA. Among the programs that have\nbeen heard the longest are: Morning De\nvotions. Cheerio. Organ Reveille. Uncle\nDon. National Farm and Home Hour,\nOrphan Annie and Amos 'n' Andy.\nQ. What are incunabula?\u2014B. P.\nA. They are specimens of early nr\nprimitive works of art or manufacture.\nIn the book world, the term is applied\nto books printed before about 1500.\nQ. Who conducted the first Cincinnati\nMusic Festival?\u2014W. R.\nA. In 1873 Cincinnati held a music\nfestival conducted by Theodore Thomas\nand the idea led to the regular festivals\nheld there since that day.\nQ. What does it indicate when an egg\nhas an exceptionally thin shell?\u2014N. H. B.\nA. Thin-shelled eggs indicate a lack\nof minerals or of vitamin D in the hens\u2019\nration.\nPart-Time Job.\nProm the Battle Creek Enqiltrer-News.\nBeing premier of Prance probably\ncomes under the head of seasonal labor.\nA Dangerous Necessity.\nProm the Grand Rapids Press.\nYes, the stock exchange Is necessary.\nSo is dynamite, but that doesn't Justify\nallowing kids to play with it.\nGood Old Slogan!\nProm the Kalamazoo Gaaette.\nWith wars popping up in other cor\nners of the globe, we might make an\naddition to the old vacation slogan: \u201cSee\nAmerica first\u2014and come back alive.\u201d\ntors. Doyle acquired international fame\nin 1916 as counsel for 8ir Roger Case\nment, the Irish rebel tried and executed\nat London for World War treason.\n(Copyrlcht, 1938.)","height":"31076","width":"22268"}}
